{"id":854,"date":"2021-04-14T03:08:47","date_gmt":"2021-04-14T03:08:47","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/programming.sdarobotics.org\/?page_id=854"},"modified":"2024-11-24T19:27:43","modified_gmt":"2024-11-24T19:27:43","slug":"building-the-nerfbot","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/building-the-nerfbot\/","title":{"rendered":"Building the Nerfbot"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The <strong>Nerfbot <\/strong>is a robot which has a nerf ball shooter mounted on a turret which is controlled by a camera. This is the robot that is used in the <strong><a href=\"\/nerfbot\/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"252\">Nerfbot tutorial<\/a><\/strong>. Most of the parts are 3D printed and the following chapters describe it&#8217;s construction and wiring.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Before we begin, lets take a look at the electronics. The robot is controlled by a Raspberry Pi which is connected to a Microcontroller Board via an I2C connection. The Microcontroller we are using is a STM32F103C8T6 in a single board commonly know as a Blue Pill. The Microcontroller Board layout is shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2365\" width=\"580\" height=\"416\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller-300x215.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller-150x108.jpg 150w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Controller-768x551.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 580px) 100vw, 580px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>There are three <strong>Motor Connectors<\/strong>, each of which can drive two motors. There are five connectors for <strong>Quadrature Encoders<\/strong>. There are four general purpose <strong>IO<\/strong> connections. Finally there is one <strong>I2C<\/strong> connector for connection to the <strong>Gyro<\/strong> and a <strong>Serial Connector<\/strong> used only for debugging. Let&#8217;s take a look at each of the connector types in detail:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is one of the <strong>Quadrature Encoder<\/strong> connection showing each pin&#8217;s function.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"386\" height=\"261\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/QuadController.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2367\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/QuadController.jpg 386w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/QuadController-300x203.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/QuadController-150x101.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 386px) 100vw, 386px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Each of the <strong>Motor Connectors<\/strong> can control two motors. The pin connections are as shown.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"428\" height=\"239\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/MotorConnector.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2370\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/MotorConnector.jpg 428w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/MotorConnector-300x168.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/MotorConnector-150x84.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 428px) 100vw, 428px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The <strong>IO Connector<\/strong> can be configured as either an input or output. The pin connections are as shown.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"266\" height=\"220\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/IOConnector.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2372\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/IOConnector.jpg 266w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/IOConnector-150x124.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 266px) 100vw, 266px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The <strong>Gyro Connector<\/strong> is used to connect the <strong>Microcontroller <\/strong>to the <strong>Gyro <\/strong>via an <strong>I2C <\/strong>connection. The pin connections are as shown.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"367\" height=\"225\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/GyroConnector.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2374\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/GyroConnector.jpg 367w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/GyroConnector-300x184.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/GyroConnector-150x92.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 367px) 100vw, 367px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The <strong>Serial Connection<\/strong> allows you to connect the <strong>Microcontroller <\/strong>to a serial port on your computer. This is only used for debugging. The pin connections are as shown.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"323\" height=\"223\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/SerialConnection.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2378\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/SerialConnection.jpg 323w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/SerialConnection-300x207.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/SerialConnection-150x104.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 323px) 100vw, 323px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"\/the-parts-2\/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"861\">Next: The Parts<\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The Nerfbot is a robot which has a nerf ball shooter mounted on a turret which is controlled by a camera. This is the robot that is used in the Nerfbot tutorial. Most 